post_text:
The Waverly-Shell Rock Community School District is committed to providing a positive educational environment for all students and expects students to model appropriate behavior during any school-sponsored activity. Heckling and taunting of any kind is not tolerated behavior for any spectators at our games, especially where this behavior is directed at a person or group based on race, color, or any other personal characteristic.

The District has completed an extensive investigation into reports that, at a baseball game on June 27, 2020 against the Charles City Community School District, racially motivated comments were directed toward a player for Charles City. Because all individuals involved are students, federal and state law prohibit the District from releasing specific findings and actions relating to this matter, but our District is taking appropriate measures in response to this incident.

post_text:
Waverly-Shell Rock schools fully acknowledge that there was an incident at a recent baseball game that had one of our fans make extremely inappropriate, bigoted comments towards a Charles City player.

This behavior is unacceptable. We make no excuses, because there are none. We do, however, wish to make a sincere apology to the Charles City school district and community and, in particular, the young man towards whom these comments were directed.

We can’t undo what’s been done. But we are using this as a learning experience for the responsible party and, we hope, for many others in our schools and communities.

Waverly-Shell Rock Administration

Update for Parents:

USDA has provided recent approval for W-SR to distribute meals from W-SR Middle School, 501 Heritage Way, Waverly, Iowa.

We encourage all those driving vehicles to pick up meals, to line up on the south side of the Middle School for pick up starting Thursday, April 9th, 11:00am- 12:30pm. Traffic will continue to be directed and meals distributed by volunteers. People may also walk or bike to the site.

The Southeast meals site will remain open for those that walk or bike to Southeast Elementary for pick up. A limited amount of meals will be available for those picking up meals by walking or by bike.

We will continue meal service through the new extended closure of April 30th.

Becky Prostine

post_text: As a follow-up to our last post. We don't yet have answers to most questions that are being asked. We are hopeful that some of those will be addressed early next week, and will be communicating with parents and students when we have those answers. Understand that some of the larger questions (such as when we will reopen, and others) will remain unanswered for some time. Again, we know there are many questions, so please be patient as we seek guidance ourselves.

post_text: Waverly-Shell Rock schools will remain closed until further notice. We know there are a lot of questions that range from things like when we might reopen, the accumulation of graduation credits, what happens to events like prom and Commencement, and everything in between. At this time we simply don't know the answers. Once these things are determined, we will be sure to let parents/guardians and students know. We appreciate your patience during this very challenging time. Please continue to do what you can to stay well.

post_text:
Tomorrow Governor Reynolds will be providing more details regarding her recommendation that schools close for four weeks. Our spring break this week provides us with some time to determine how Waverly-Shell Rock will respond. We have several administrators and board members out of the district this week, so please be patient as we work through all the details. It’s an unprecedented time that will call for careful consideration.

Thank you

As a result of several challenges encountered with SchoolMessenger, we have been seeking an alternative solution for notifications--particularly in regards to instances related to weather. We believe we have found something that will work for us. We encourage you to copy and paste the URL found at the bottom of this message into your browser. Once on that page you can sign up to receive text messages or emails when a notice is posted.

We're sorry about the hassle of dealing with another notification system, but this one will be a better option for everyone who needs to be notified in a timely manner. And that includes people who are not in our Infinite Campus system.

Feel free to share the link with anyone you believe needs to be made aware of weather-related announcements.

https://public.govdelivery.com/accounts/IAEDU6840/subscriber/topics?qsp=CODE_RED

Did you know that you can be a substitute teacher with any four-year degree or a para-educator license just by taking a weekend class? The Substitute Authorization class will be offered October 25-27, 2019 in the W-SR Middle School Media Center. Classes will be 5-8 PM on Friday, then 8 AM-5 PM on both Saturday and Sunday.

In order to register go to: aealearning.truenorthlogic.com Then go to course # 3405 - Section 2722385. Any difficulties registering please contact the AEA at: 319-273-8200

These courses fill up quickly, so be sure to get registered right away. If you have any questions feel free to reach out to the Peggy Slattery (peggy.slattery@wsr.k12.ia.us).

post_text: We had an amazing group of fourth grade parents and Parent Group volunteers to head up work crews during our Southeast Elementary Clean-up Day today. All 41 fourth grade students took part and weeded and mulched the gardens around school. We had a thunderstorm roll through and couldn't get everything planned done, but the kids and parents worked wet, sticky and sweaty. They even got ALL of the rocks off the surface under the playground equipment and raked all of the stones back in place. Truly a committed group! Thank you!

post_text:
**SUMMER JOB** W-SR Parents, your child has the opportunity to serve as a Green Iowa AmeriCorps Sustainable Schools member this summer in both their school and community. In this position, students will help increase sustainability initiatives within the school district and throughout the community, assist with district-wide summer programming, and help with community and on-campus gardening and landscape maintenance.
Qualifications:
Age: 17+
Valid Driver's License

Benefits:
Living Stipend = $2,750 (total for the summer)
Education Award (Scholarship) upon successful completion of summer term: $ 1,289

Service Term:
Monday, May 20th - Friday, August 16th.
Members must complete 300 hours of service work in that time = 25-30 hours/week

For more information, take a look at: https://www.greeniowaamericorps.org/open-positions

Troy Belmer‎Alive & Running Iowa for Suicide Awareness & Prevention
December 19, 2018 at 11:25 PM ·

Today I had the opportunity to speak to four groups of about 170-200 kids for a total of almost 800 students at Waverly Shell Rock High School. Parents & faculty should be proud of the kids. They were very attentive & respectful. I’ve already gotten some very positive feedback from the kids. Special thanks to the administration & excel group from WSR for organizing this. It’s just awesome to see mental health becoming a priority #AliveAndRunningIowa #WSRCares #GoHawks

post_text: You might have noticed these signs (or similar ones) hanging around our schools. We embrace the need to support students in managing their emotions so they are ready to learn and have positive interactions at school. The “Get to Green” posters not only provide a symbol to recognize, but also common language that can help students identify their emotions and provide strategies to regulate themselves to an optimal learning state. We would also encourage you as parents to use the “Get to Green” language as way to support your son or daughter at home too.

post_text:
Recognition of our Building Principals

The month of October is designated as National Principal Recognition Month. It’s a time for us to deliberately recognize and honor the hard work and dedication of those who serve in that capacity. Waverly-Shell Rock is fortunate to have six principals serving seven buildings and over 2300 students. These six individuals— Micky Bahlmann, Donita Dettmer, David Fox, Jeremy Langner, Christi Lines, and Brady Weber—are truly dedicated to their staffs and students.

The key to student success is having a great school. And great schools don’t happen by accident. It takes a caring, dedicated staff, led by someone who understands what it takes to make it great. Principals work countless hours in support of our students and our staff, yet they are often the least recognized. We have great appreciation for the work that our principals do, and they deserve recognition for their efforts. They are truly a key component to the success of our district and, more importantly, our students.

post_text:
W-SR DECA would like to invite you to participate in a very important event. Throughout the year, Julia Reed, Molly Ramker and Britney Young, with assistance from Sadie Hansen have been hard at work on a community service project with the organization Friends of the Family to bring better awareness to the plague of human sex trafficking. An important aspect of the project is an interactive display that tells the stories of people involved in trafficking, including the victims/survivors, counseling specialists, law enforcement officers, prosecutors and even the traffickers. The display will be available today at W-SR High School from 8:15 am to 3:30 pm.

You will have your eyes opened and be challenged by what you see. A representative from Friends of the Family will be there to answer any question you have about their efforts to combat trafficking in Iowa and offer new hope to survivors.

If you want a preview of what you will see and to get more information, please visit the project website at: www.revealingthefaces.com
